 DESIGN FLAWS
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════

1. Totem assignment encoding conflates two unrelated domains in one byte

   _totemAssignment[slot] is a uint8_t that encodes two semantically
   different things depending on its value:

     • 0..COUNT-1  → a GenericTotemRoles constant (NONE=0, BONUS=1, MALUS=2)
     • COUNT..255  → a totemVar index, stored as (index + COUNT)

   COUNT is currently 3 (config.h:261), so totemVar[0] is stored as 3,
   totemVar[1] as 4, and so on.

   THE REAL PROBLEM — this creates a hidden structural dependency between
   two otherwise independent concepts. If a new generic role is added
   (e.g. SHIELD, making COUNT=4), every persisted and in-memory encoded
   value for a totemVar silently shifts by one:
     • old value 3 meant totemVar[0], now means totemVar[-1] → decoded garbage
     • old value 4 meant totemVar[1], now means totemVar[0] → wrong slot

   There is no assertion, no version check, and no compiler error. The bug
   would appear only at runtime as subtly wrong totem assignments.

   The decoding arithmetic (val - GenericTotemRoles::COUNT) is repeated at
   four independent call sites (GameSetupMenu.cpp lines 725, 969, 1019 and
   the reverse at 705, 564), all of which silently become wrong together.

   The same encoded bytes are written to a shared config blob that is
   broadcast over radio and stored to disk. Any saved session config would
   be silently misread after a COUNT change.

   SUGGESTED FIX — replace the byte with a tagged struct:

     struct TotemAssignment {
         bool    named;   // false = generic role, true = totemVar index
         uint8_t value;   // GenericTotemRoles constant  OR  totemVar index
     };

   The two domains never overlap; no arithmetic needed; adding a generic
   role has zero effect on totemVar indices. The config blob serialisation
   would need a matching change (e.g. one byte for role, one for named-idx)
   but that is an explicit, auditable migration rather than a silent shift.

2. Enlight via global pointer
   Games declare extern Enlight* enlightPtr (e.g. GameFreeForAll.cpp ~47).
   The pointer is initialized in the sketch, but nothing prevents a game
   from dereferencing it before initialization, and there's zero
   compile-time safety. Enlight should be injected into GameRunner::begin()
   or into the game callbacks as a parameter.

4. Config blob truncation is silent
   game_apply_config() has no total-length check. A truncated blob
   (e.g. partial radio delivery) passes the typeId check and is
   deserialized by fixed offset arithmetic, silently producing garbage
   configVar / totemVar values. The function returns false only on
   typeId mismatch or buffer shorter than 2 bytes.


